      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Contract Variation After Signing in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A signed contract is not the end of the negotiation. Here's how sellers and buyers in Queensland can formally vary a contract after signing, what kinds of changes are possible, and how to handle them without putting the deal at risk.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A contract of sale in Queensland is a serious commitment, but it is not the end of the negotiation. In practice, a meaningful percentage of residential conveyancing transactions in the inner Brisbane market involve at least one variation between signing and settlement. The building and pest inspector identifies something unexpected. The buyer's finance approval slips by a week. A special condition needs to be reworded to satisfy someone's solicitor. The seller discovers a document issue that needs to be addressed before settlement can occur. Each of these moments is a negotiation: one party is asking the other to agree to a change in the terms they have already signed, and the outcome depends on how cleanly that conversation is handled.</p>

      <p>This article walks through the legal starting point for contract variations in Queensland, the most common reasons variations are requested, how they are documented, what can and cannot easily be changed, and the practical considerations for sellers and buyers who find themselves needing to adjust the deal mid-conveyance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal starting point</h2>
      <p>A contract of sale can be varied at any point after signing, but only by the mutual agreement of both parties. One party cannot unilaterally change a term. If the buyer wants a longer settlement, the seller has to agree. If the seller wants to remove a special condition, the buyer has to agree. The variation has to be in writing, and it has to be signed by both parties to be effective. In Queensland this is typically done through a short amendment letter or a formal variation of contract document, prepared by one party's solicitor, signed by both parties and their solicitors, and filed alongside the original contract.</p>

      <p>The legal theory behind this is straightforward: a variation is a new agreement about the terms of the original deal, and like any agreement it requires mutual consent, consideration (sometimes nominal, sometimes substantive), and a clear record. Oral agreements to vary the contract are risky. They may be legally effective in narrow circumstances, but they create evidentiary problems that almost always come back to bite someone at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common reasons a variation is requested</h2>
      <p>The most frequent reasons for a variation in Queensland residential contracts tend to cluster around a few predictable pressure points in the conveyancing timeline. The buyer's finance approval runs past the finance date and needs an extension of a few days or a week. The building and pest inspection identifies an issue significant enough that the buyer wants either a price adjustment or additional vendor remediation before settlement. The buyer's solicitor wants a special condition reworded for clarity or to address a specific risk. The seller discovers a document or title issue that needs to be resolved before settlement can complete, requiring an extended settlement date. Both parties agree to bring settlement forward because finance and other logistics have come together faster than expected.</p>

      <p>None of these is a sign of a failed deal. They are the normal friction of a 30 to 45 day conveyance where new information surfaces as each side conducts their due diligence. Good solicitors handle them as routine, and the deal continues. Poor handling of a variation, on the other hand, can escalate a minor issue into a lost sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How variations are documented</h2>
      <p>The standard practice in Queensland is for the party requesting the variation to ask their solicitor to draft a short amendment letter setting out the proposed change. The letter references the original contract (by date, parties, and property), states the specific term being varied, sets out the new term, and requests the other party's signature. The other party's solicitor reviews the amendment, advises their client, and either signs off, proposes a counter-amendment, or refuses. Once both parties sign, the amendment letter forms part of the contract and is treated as a legally binding variation.</p>

      <p>For more complex variations, such as a material price reduction tied to a defect identified in the building inspection, the documentation is usually more detailed. It will record not just the new price, but also any new conditions, the consideration each side is providing for the change, and the treatment of deposits if part of the deposit has already been paid. Proper documentation is especially important if the variation has any flow-on implications for transfer duty or for the financier's valuation. Rushing this step to save a day or two is almost always a false economy.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What cannot be easily varied</h2>
      <p>Some changes are technically possible but practically difficult, and some are effectively impossible within the framework of a variation. The identity of the buyer or seller cannot be simply varied: replacing the named buyer with a different entity usually requires a contract novation, which is a fundamentally different legal step and may trigger its own stamp duty and contract consequences. The property being sold cannot be changed: if the parties want to substitute one lot for another, they typically need to terminate the original contract and sign a new one. Material changes to the price, particularly significant reductions, can attract scrutiny from the Queensland Revenue Office if they appear designed to minimise transfer duty liability, and need to be documented with the genuine commercial rationale clear on the face of the variation.</p>

      <p>These edge cases are the kind of thing where solicitor advice is not optional. An amendment that looks simple on paper can have cascading consequences for duty, for any financier's approval, or for the legal validity of the contract as a whole if it is drafted badly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Price reduction instead of termination</h2>
      <p>The most frequently valuable use of a variation in Queensland conveyancing is a negotiated price reduction following a building and pest inspection. The standard contract gives the buyer the right to terminate on the basis of an unsatisfactory building or pest report. Terminating and walking away is always an option, but in many cases the buyer actually still wants the property, and the seller still wants the deal. In those situations the sensible outcome is usually a price variation that reflects the scope of the work the buyer will need to carry out post-settlement, rather than a termination that sends both parties back to square one.</p>

      <p>The negotiation on the price reduction is usually informed by quotes the buyer has obtained for the remediation. A reputable buyer will share the quotes with the seller, and a reasonable seller will accept that something like a fair share of the repair cost is the price of keeping the deal alive. Variations of this kind are routine and produce much better net outcomes than termination, for both sides. The variation document records the new price clearly, notes any change in the deposit if the deposit has already been lodged, and confirms the other terms of the contract are unchanged.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Extensions of settlement</h2>
      <p>Settlement extensions are the single most common variation. The Queensland standard contract provides for settlement on a specific date, and both parties are obligated to be ready to settle on that day. If either party cannot, the other party has rights, including the right to issue a notice to complete and terminate if completion does not occur within the notice period. In practice, most minor delays are dealt with by a short variation extending settlement by a few days, often with no consideration required. For longer extensions, or where one party is materially inconvenienced by the delay, the extending party may offer compensation, such as interest on the deposit, a contribution to rates adjustments, or some other negotiated benefit.</p>

      <p>The key detail with settlement extensions is that they need to be documented and signed before the original settlement date, not after. An extension granted informally on the day can leave both parties in legal limbo about whether the contract is still alive. Solicitors on both sides will usually insist on the formality for good reason.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Special condition changes</h2>
      <p>Adding, amending, or removing a special condition is possible by mutual agreement. Adding a new condition after signing typically favours the buyer, because it introduces a new way the buyer can exit the deal if the condition is not satisfied. Removing a condition typically favours the seller, because it removes one of those exit rights. Amendments to the wording of existing conditions can go either way. Because every change in the special conditions shifts the risk balance, sellers should be cautious about agreeing to new conditions after signing without understanding how they change the buyer's ability to walk, and buyers should be equally cautious about agreeing to remove conditions without understanding what rights they are giving up.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should insist on</h2>
      <p>Three rules for sellers considering any variation request. First, nothing is agreed until it is in writing and signed by both parties; a verbal agreement to vary is not enforceable in most circumstances and is not worth the risk. Second, the variation must be reviewed by your solicitor before you sign, not after; the cost of the review is trivial compared to the cost of signing away a right you did not realise you had. Third, any consideration you are providing (a lower price, an extended date, a waived condition) should be matched by consideration coming back the other way in the variation; variations are negotiations, and you should treat the other party's willingness to ask as an opportunity to secure something in return.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers should be aware of</h2>
      <p>Buyers should understand that every time they ask for a variation, they are signalling that they are flexible. A seller who feels the buyer is difficult or is repeatedly asking for changes may either refuse subsequent requests or demand compensating consideration. Buyers who accumulate a series of small variation requests risk eroding the seller's goodwill toward the deal, and a frustrated seller is a seller who is more likely to terminate at the first legal opportunity rather than accommodate the next request. Where possible, variations should be consolidated into a single conversation rather than drip-fed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Variations are a normal and useful part of Queensland conveyancing, not a sign of a broken deal. Handled through solicitors, documented properly, and signed before the relevant deadlines, they are the tool that keeps a deal alive when new information surfaces or circumstances change. Handled informally, verbally, or late, they become the tool that breaks deals that could otherwise have settled cleanly. The best advice for both sides is to treat every variation request as a small, properly documented negotiation, to resist the urge to agree to anything off-the-cuff, and to use each variation to tighten rather than loosen the overall contract structure.</p>

      <p>For most sellers and buyers in the inner Brisbane market, the conveyance will run from contract to settlement with one or two minor variations along the way. Understanding how they work before you need one turns them from a source of anxiety into a routine part of getting to the settlement table.</p>

